The area

Address
Neighborhood: Centrum
Amsterdam’s buzzing hub, with its sprawling network of tram rails and a seemingly constant flow of tourists and commuters, yields convenient access to some of the best sightseeing, shopping, and street life in Europe. Closest at hand are the Royal Palace, the quaint shops of Haalremmerdijk, the pedestrianized zones Kalverstraat and Dam Square with popular neighborhoods such as the Red Light District, and the Canal Ring hardly more than a moment’s stroll away. With the well-connected Centraal Station as Centrum’s base, it's easy to travel farther afield via one of the city’s iconic trams.
How to get there
  • Centraal Station • 7 min walk
  • Nieuwmarkt • 8 min walk

    Beautiful and Huge
    I originally had planned to spend part of the day working remotely from the library on my last day in Amsterdam before taking the Nightjet train to München. As luck would have it, my Airbnb hosts graciously let me stay late into the afternoon on my final day so I did not need to use the library, but I did stop by the library for a bit to have lunch and check out how practical it would be to work from there. They had an overwhelming number of places where you could work, with outlets and good lighting. I did quickly try to get on to the internet, but struggled a bit and did not take the time to get it figured out. I'm sure the staff could have helped if I had asked. The cafe at the top had nice food and a beautiful view from the terrace.

  • Herbert C

    Superb place to enjoy a breathtaking view and a toilet break (and it’s free!)
    Here's a secret tip while you're in Amsterdam........ Where’s the best free place to take a toilet break and enjoy the view of Amsterdam? Yes, it's none other than the OBA Oosterdok, the Central Branch of the Openbare Bibliotheek Amsterdam (Amsterdam Public Library). Opened in 2007, the OBA Oosterdok is actually the 2nd largest library in Europe by floor space, behind the Library of Birmingham in the UK. Located in the eastern docklands within a short walking distance from the Amsterdam Central Station, this public library boasts 10 floors, more than 1,000 seats, 1.5 million of catalogues items, a 300-seats theatre, and opening hours of 90 hours per week (which is double the average opening hours of the conventional libraries in Europe). Best of all, on the top floor (7th floor) is a cafe-restaurant with a terrace that offers spectacular panoramic views over the city. There's no better place to spend a couple of hours especially when it rains in Amsterdam. The best things in life are indeed free!
    Visited June 2024
    Traveled solo

Great place to visit and great selection of food including vegan and vegetarian options.1
Jun 2023 • Couples
We visited for lunch in the cafe not for the library. The selection of food and drink on offer was really very good and varied in choice. He priests are cheaper than you will pay in city. Inside tables and seating outside with views of the city. Friendly staff, bright and clean restaurant. Nice free views across to the south side of the city.
Free ferry from central station. You can also use the free ferries to travel further up or down the river. Yes a FREE trip or trips. For library 5 min journey. Other trip along was about 12 minutes. If you have children they would love the boat rides.
The library itself is light and bright with some nice display cabinets to look at.
Other places to visit this side too especially if you have a bike or moped. You can travel free with those too.
